## What Is an Elongated Cushion Cut Lab Grown Diamond

An elongated cushion cut lab grown diamond is a cushion-shaped diamond grown in a laboratory — using either HPHT (High Pressure High Temperature) or CVD (Chemical Vapor Deposition) process — with a length-to-width ratio of 1.10 or higher, producing a stone that is measurably longer than it is wide. The "elongated" designation applies the same L/W ratio criteria as it does for natural cushions: below 1.10 is near-square; 1.10–1.14 is the no-man's-land; 1.15–1.25 is The Ratio Sweet Spot where elongation is unambiguous without sacrificing the cushion's soft-corner character; above 1.25 the cushion begins reading as a rounded rectangle. Lab origin does not change the L/W ratio dynamics, the optical performance, or the cutting sub-type — it changes only the origin, the certification choices, and the price-to-quality ratio, all of which improve dramatically for the lab grown stone.

Lab grown diamonds are chemically, physically, and optically identical to natural diamonds — same carbon crystal structure, same 10/10 Mohs hardness, same refractive index, same fire and brilliance. A gemologist cannot distinguish a lab grown elongated cushion from a natural one without a laboratory report; even grading laboratories need advanced spectroscopy equipment, not visual examination. The only meaningful differences are price (lab is 70–90% lower at equivalent quality), resale value (lab: 5–20% of purchase; natural: 30–50%), and GIA lab certification cost premium covered in the IGI vs GIA section below.

The elongated cushion is the lab grown diamond category's strongest growth segment in {{year}} because the combination of lab pricing and the elongated cushion's face-up size efficiency is uniquely powerful. At a $3,000 total ring budget, a natural elongated cushion buyer is looking at 0.75–1ct stones in G-VS1 quality; a lab buyer at the same budget can build a ring around a 1.5ct D-VVS2 elongated cushion. The resulting ring looks dramatically different — not because lab diamonds are more beautiful, but because the budget goes an order of magnitude further in stone size.

## The Elongation Divide

**The Elongation Divide is the visual discontinuity that occurs at different L/W ratio ranges for cushion cuts — the reason a 1.12 and a 1.22 ratio cushion, separated by only 0.10 in their ratio number, look like fundamentally different stones on the finger.** For lab grown elongated cushion buyers specifically, The Elongation Divide is a shopping problem because Blue Nile's cushion diamond search does not separate elongated from standard cushions — the results default to showing all L/W ratios, and most inventory is near-square (1.00–1.08). Buyers who search "lab cushion" without filtering L/W ratio are looking at a mix of square and elongated stones with no visual signal to tell them apart.

At L/W ratios below 1.10, a cushion sits balanced and square — the pillow aesthetic is present, but no elongation. Between 1.10 and 1.14, the stone is in the no-man's-land of the Elongation Divide: elongated enough to look slightly off-square, but not elongated enough to read as intentionally elongated — buyers in this range frequently report that the stone looked different in person than expected. At 1.15 and above, elongation becomes unambiguous: the stone clearly reads as longer-than-wide, the soft corners are visible along the narrower ends, and the optical finger-lengthening effect activates when the stone is set.

**The practical lab shopping implication of The Elongation Divide:** when searching Blue Nile's lab cushion inventory, filter by L/W ratio explicitly. The target is 1.15–1.25. Below 1.15 is no-man's-land; above 1.25 the cushion character erodes toward rectangular. For 3ct+ lab cushions where multiple stones are available at the same price tier, the one with L/W closest to 1.20 is the correct choice in almost every case — it is the single most stable ratio for elongated cushion visual performance across all hand sizes and setting styles.

> "The Elongation Divide catches lab grown cushion buyers off guard more than any other factor — they buy a stone labeled 'elongated cushion,' receive it, and find it reads as near-square because the L/W ratio was 1.10 or 1.11. Lab stones are unreturnably set before this is discovered in many cases. Always request the exact L/W ratio from the listing before purchasing, and require that it falls within 1.15–1.25 before committing."
> — Farzana, Diamond Consultant

## IGI vs GIA for Elongated Cushion Lab Grown Diamonds

The certification choice for elongated cushion lab grown diamonds is one of the most consequential buying decisions in this category, and the data is unambiguous: IGI is the better choice for lab grown stones at every carat tier. GIA lab grown certification carries a significantly higher certification fee that passes through to the buyer's price — not because GIA-certified lab stones are cut better, measured more accurately, or graded more stringently for the stones themselves, but because GIA's lab division pricing structure is different from IGI's. The result: GIA-certified lab grown elongated cushions cost 40–140% more than IGI-certified equivalents at the same actual stone quality.

