The price-per-carat curve for lab grown elongated cushions drops dramatically from 1ct ($680/ct) to 3ct ($2,072/ct for D-VVS1) to 4ct ($1,853/ct for D-VVS1) — economies of scale favor larger stones significantly. This curve is the primary reason the 3ct elongated cushion lab grown is the category's most searched and purchased tier: the per-carat cost drops sharply from 1ct to 3ct, but barely moves from 3ct to 4ct, making 3ct the inflection point where size and value intersect most favorably.

## Elongated Cushion Lab Grown 2 Carat

The elongated cushion lab grown 2 carat is the category's price-performance peak in {{year}}. A [2ct IGI D-VVS1 lab cushion at $2,606](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28884982?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) delivers D color (colorless) and VVS1 clarity at a price below what a natural G-VS2 1ct cushion commands — the stone is visually flawless, larger than any natural stone available at this budget, and certifiably D-grade colorless. A natural 2ct G-VS1 cushion at equivalent market pricing would run approximately $8,500–$12,000 depending on cut quality and length-to-width ratio, making the lab 2ct offering roughly 70–80% cheaper with objectively superior color and clarity grades.

The 2ct elongated cushion at L/W 1.20 measures approximately 8.4mm × 7.0mm face-up — a significantly larger face-up footprint than a 2ct round brilliant (6.5mm diameter) and dramatically larger than any 1ct stone. On an average finger width (size 6–7), a 2ct elongated cushion at this ratio fills the finger from side to side with visible length-to-width contrast and produces the finger-lengthening effect at its most flattering scale. This is why the 2ct elongated cushion is the single most popular complete ring build target in the lab grown cushion category.

At the [IGI 2ct D-IF tier ($4,782)](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/27980784?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational), the buyer gets D color and internally flawless clarity in a 2ct elongated cushion — a specification that would cost $25,000–$40,000 in natural at this size. For the buyer who wants the absolute best measurable quality (D-IF or D-FL) and cares about the grading certificate as a statement of quality rather than as a resale instrument, this tier delivers at a fraction of natural cost.

