## Elongated Cushion Lab Grown 3 Carat

The elongated cushion lab grown 3 carat is where lab origin becomes not just the smart choice but the defining characteristic of the entire product tier. A [GIA 3ct D-VVS1 lab cushion at $5,962](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/26315453?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the most remarkable price-quality combination in diamond retail in {{year}}: D color, VVS1 clarity, 3 full carats of cushion modified brilliant diamond, GIA certified, at $5,962. The same specification in natural — GIA 3ct D-VVS1 cushion — would cost approximately $65,000–$100,000+ based on current natural 3ct cushion market pricing.

At the [IGI 3ct D-VVS1 entry at $6,215](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/25630512?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational), buyers get effectively the same stone with an IGI certificate. Multiple IGI 3ct D-IF lab cushion stones are available at [$9,327](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/26749422?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) — D color and internally flawless clarity in a 3ct stone for under $10,000. Natural diamonds at this specification at 3ct do not exist at any price point accessible to a normal consumer; they are museum-acquisition stones.

A 3ct elongated cushion at L/W 1.20 measures approximately 9.5mm × 7.9mm face-up. On most finger widths, this is a genuinely large ring that reads as a statement piece rather than an everyday ring — it commands attention in any lighting condition and produces the elongated cushion's continuous, distributed sparkle along a nearly 10mm expanse across the finger. For buyers who want maximum visual presence in an elongated cushion lab grown diamond, the 3ct tier is the category's apex, and the [IGI 3ct D-VVS1 at $6,215](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/25630512?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the specific stone to start with.

## The Lab Sovereign

**The Lab Sovereign describes the market condition at 3ct and above in the elongated cushion diamond category: natural supply at any reasonable quality has effectively dried up, natural pricing has reached levels inaccessible to the vast majority of buyers, and lab grown diamonds dominate the market so completely that buying natural at this tier is more exceptional purchase than rational purchase.** At 3ct, natural GIA elongated cushion diamonds with G-VS quality start at $32,692; D-IF natural cushions at 3ct reach $78,575. The same carat and quality specifications in IGI lab grown start at $6,215 (D-VVS1) and $9,327 (D-IF). The cost delta is not 20% or even 50% — it is 5–10× for equivalent measurable specifications.

The Lab Sovereign applies at the carat threshold where natural supply becomes genuinely scarce in the elongated ratio specifically. Standard (square) 3ct cushion natural stones are available at moderate prices because the 1.00–1.05 L/W range is abundant in production; elongated natural cushions at 3ct with L/W 1.15–1.25 in G or better color and VS or better clarity represent a tiny fraction of natural cushion production, making them rare and expensive in ways that square cushions are not. Lab grown production faces no such constraint: elongated L/W ratios can be targeted during growth and cutting, and 3ct lab cushions at D-VVS1 or better are genuinely abundant.

**The Lab Sovereign has a practical decision rule built into it:** any buyer considering an elongated cushion at 3ct or above should default to lab grown unless they have a specific and non-negotiable requirement for natural provenance. Natural elongated cushions at 3ct exist and can be found — they are beautiful, certifiably rare, and they hold resale value better than lab stones. But they are approximately 10× more expensive for equivalent grades, and no buyer looking at them face-up under normal conditions will see 10× more beauty. The Lab Sovereign tier is where the lab vs natural debate is essentially settled by the market itself.

> "The Lab Sovereign tier is a concept I explain to every client who comes in asking about a 3ct cushion. I show them the numbers: a GIA D-VVS1 natural 3ct cushion at over $70,000 compared to a GIA D-VVS1 lab 3ct at $5,962. I ask them to hold both under normal lighting and find the difference. They can't — because there isn't one the eye can detect. At that point the conversation changes: it becomes about what the ring means, not what the stone is made of."
> — Farzana, Diamond Consultant

